5. Create a bipartite network representing links between members of congress and the subcommittees they are associated with. Keep this graph for future problems.

HINT: you can create a bipartite network by assigning values to the type node attribute. You can verify that you have a bipartite network by using the is_bipartite function. You will have problems later on if your graph is not bipartite.

HINT: you will again need to join committee_memberships with subcommittees to remove the full committee memberships.

# Your answer here.
elist <- subcommittees %>% 
  inner_join(committee_memberships, on=thomas_id) %>% 
  select(bioguide_id, thomas_id)
## Joining, by = "thomas_id"
g <- graph_from_data_frame(elist)
V(g)$type <- V(g)$name %in% elist$bioguide_id
is_bipartite(g)
## [1] TRUE


6. Create an adjacency matrix that you further use to make a new graph. Was the bipartite property preserved in the graph created from the adjacency matrix? Why does igraph work this way?

# Your answer here
A <- g %>% as_adjacency_matrix()
p <- graph_from_adjacency_matrix(A)
dim(A)
## [1] 693 693
is_bipartite(p)
## [1] FALSE
Bipartite property was not preserved because adjacency matrix does not inherently contain information about which nodes are associated with which group (congress members or committees). We can see that from the fact that dim(A) is the same as the total number of nodes in the graph here.

HINT: see the section on using bipartite_projection in the required reading “Bipartite/Two-Mode Networks in igraph.” You can download their data to see how they use it.

HINT: the function bipartite_projection produces two separate networks - read the documentation to see the meaning of each, and make sure you’re using the network of politicians instead of the network of committees.

HINT: You can get the edge weights of a network using E(g)$weight. You can add any number of edge attributes to an igraph network, but the weight attribute is a special attribute used by many igraph functions and, in this case, automatically populated by bipartite_projection according to the number of common committees the congress members are on.

9. Calculate the strength (weighted degree), eigenvalue, closeness, and betweenness centrality for each politician in this network, and compute the correlations between all of them. Why are some of the correlations negative?

Hint: read the documentation for the centrality calculation functions carefully. The important difference is in how the edge weights are interpreted. This is an important consideration when thinking about the types of centrality you want to use for your analysis.

# Yor answer here or in text.
centralities <- data.frame(strength=strength(h), eigen=eigen_centrality(h)$vector, closeness=closeness(h), betweenness=betweenness(h))
## Warning in closeness(h): At centrality.c:2701 :closeness centrality is not well-
## defined for disconnected graphs
centralities %>% cor()
##                 strength      eigen  closeness  betweenness
## strength     1.000000000  0.6691874 -0.5668088 -0.008524269
## eigen        0.669187408  1.0000000 -0.9094709 -0.297199939
## closeness   -0.566808784 -0.9094709  1.0000000  0.311253502
## betweenness -0.008524269 -0.2971999  0.3112535  1.000000000
Strength and eigenvector consider edge weights to be the "strength" of a tie (like how close two friends are), whereas closeness and betweenness consider edge weights to be a distance (like distances on a map). Only strength and eigenvector centrality are relevant, because we'd consider congress members to be more closely related if they are on more common committees.

9. In last week’s lab exercise, you were asked to identify several possible datasets you could use for your final project. Now write two specific data science research questions and describe variables in that dataset that could allow you to answer the questions.

HINT: What is a good research question? A good data science research question specifies a relationship between two or more variables that you can measure. The question “why did the chicken cross the road?” is not a good research question because it does not explicitly describe the relationship between any variables. The question “do chickens cross the road more frequently than raccoons?” is good because it specifies a relationship between the type of animal (chickens and raccoons) and the frequency with which the animal crosses the road. Your question should be answerable given the specific variables available in your dataset.
